# ============================================================
# CURSOR RULES — Wound Segmentation U-Net Project
# Bachelor's Thesis: AI-Powered Chronic Wound Monitoring
# ============================================================
# These rules guide Cursor's AI when helping you write code.
# Keep this file in the project root. Never delete it.

## PROJECT CONTEXT
This is a PyTorch deep learning project for semantic segmentation of chronic wounds
(diabetic foot ulcers, venous leg ulcers, pressure injuries) using a U-Net architecture.
The goal is a bachelor's thesis with publishable-quality metrics.

## TECH STACK
- Python 3.10+
- PyTorch 2.x + torchvision
- scikit-learn (ALL metrics computation)
- albumentations (image augmentation)
- matplotlib + seaborn (plots)
- tqdm (progress bars)
- PIL / Pillow (image I/O)
- numpy, pandas

## CODE STYLE RULES
1. Always use type hints on all function signatures
2. Every function must have a docstring explaining: what it does, args, returns
3. Use f-strings for all string formatting (no .format() or %)
4. Constants go in config.py — never hardcode paths or hyperparameters inline
5. Device handling: always use `device = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")`
6. Never use bare `except:` — always catch specific exceptions
7. Log important steps with print() including epoch, loss, and metrics
8. Use `torch.no_grad()` context manager during validation/inference — never forget this

## ARCHITECTURE RULES
- U-Net encoder uses pretrained ResNet34 backbone (transfer learning from ImageNet)
- Input images: RGB, resized to 256x256
- Output: single-channel binary mask (sigmoid activation → threshold at 0.5)
- Loss function: BCEWithLogitsLoss + Dice Loss combined (never use BCE alone)
- Optimizer: Adam with lr=1e-4
- Scheduler: ReduceLROnPlateau monitoring validation IoU

## METRICS RULES (from classification_metrics.pdf)
ALWAYS compute and report ALL of these metrics during validation:
- Confusion matrix values: TP, TN, FP, FN
- Accuracy         → (TP+TN)/(TP+TN+FP+FN)
- Precision (PPV)  → TP/(TP+FP)          [PDF #8]
- Recall (TPR)     → TP/(TP+FN)          [PDF #7]  ← prioritize this for wounds
- Specificity(TNR) → TN/(TN+FP)          [PDF #4]
- FPR (Type I)     → FP/(FP+TN)          [PDF #2]
- FNR (Type II)    → FN/(TP+FN)          [PDF #3]
- F1 Score / Dice  → 2*P*R/(P+R)         [PDF #11] ← PRIMARY metric
- MCC              → matthews_corrcoef    [PDF #14]
- ROC AUC          → roc_auc_score        [PDF #16]
- PR AUC           → average_precision   [PDF #18]
- IoU / Jaccard    → intersection/union  ← SEGMENTATION standard (target ≥ 0.75)
- Dice coefficient → 2*intersection/(sum) ← equals F1 at pixel level

In segmentation, EVERY PIXEL is a binary classification — background(0) or wound(1).
This is why all metrics from the PDF directly apply here.

## DATA RULES
- images/ → RGB wound photos (.jpg or .png)
- masks/  → binary segmentation masks (.png): white=wound(255), black=background(0)
- Filename pairing: image "001.jpg" → mask "001.png" (same stem, different extension)
- Train/Val/Test split: 70% / 15% / 15% — always use random seed 42 for reproducibility
- Always normalize images with ImageNet mean/std: mean=[0.485,0.456,0.406] std=[0.229,0.224,0.225]
- Always apply augmentation ONLY to training set, never to validation or test

## AUGMENTATION RULES (albumentations)
Training augmentations (in this order):
1. HorizontalFlip(p=0.5)
2. VerticalFlip(p=0.3)
3. RandomRotate90(p=0.5)
4. RandomBrightnessContrast(p=0.3)
5. HueSaturationValue(p=0.2)        ← simulates different lighting/cameras
6. GaussianBlur(p=0.1)
7. GridDistortion(p=0.2)            ← elastic deformation for wound shapes
IMPORTANT: apply SAME transform to both image and mask (albumentations handles this)

## FILE ORGANIZATION RULES
- src/config.py      → ALL hyperparameters and paths (single source of truth)
- src/dataset.py     → WoundDataset class only
- src/model.py       → UNet class only
- src/losses.py      → BCEDiceLoss class only
- src/metrics.py     → ALL metric functions (matches PDF)
- src/train.py       → training loop only
- src/evaluate.py    → full evaluation with plots
- src/predict.py     → inference on new images
- tests/             → unit tests for each module
- notebooks/         → Jupyter exploratory analysis only

## REPRODUCIBILITY RULES
Always set seeds at the start of train.py:
    torch.manual_seed(42)
    torch.cuda.manual_seed(42)
    np.random.seed(42)
    random.seed(42)
    torch.backends.cudnn.deterministic = True

## SAVING RULES
- Save best model checkpoint when val IoU improves: checkpoints/best_model.pth
- Save last epoch checkpoint: checkpoints/last_model.pth
- Save metrics history to: results/metrics/history.csv
- Save confusion matrix plot to: results/plots/confusion_matrix.png
- Save ROC curve plot to: results/plots/roc_curve.png
- Save PR curve plot to: results/plots/pr_curve.png

## THESIS WRITING TIPS (for Cursor to remember)
- Target IoU ≥ 0.75 (literature benchmark for wound segmentation)
- Target Dice/F1 ≥ 0.80
- Target ROC AUC ≥ 0.90
- Always compare results against published FUSeg challenge baselines
- For the thesis, Recall is MORE important than Precision (missing a wound is worse than a false alarm)
- MCC is the most balanced single metric — mention it prominently in defense
